WEBVTT

00:00.828 --> 00:04.211
[static crackling]

00:08.180 --> 00:11.149
[soft music]

00:11.183 --> 00:16.844
♪

00:16.878 --> 00:19.329
- New York City
during the 1970s

00:19.364 --> 00:22.746
was a beautiful,
ravaged slag...

00:22.781 --> 00:24.541
[loud distortion]

00:24.576 --> 00:25.853
[soft music resumes]

00:25.887 --> 00:27.613
Impoverished and neglected

00:27.648 --> 00:31.617
after suffering from decades
of abuse and battery.

00:31.652 --> 00:34.344
She stunk of sewage, sex,

00:34.379 --> 00:36.691
rotting fish,
and day-old diapers.

00:36.726 --> 00:39.556
She leaked from every pore.

00:39.591 --> 00:41.282
- [screams]

00:41.317 --> 00:43.077
[punk rock music,
early hip-hop music]

00:43.112 --> 00:44.630
[soft music resumes]

00:44.665 --> 00:47.633
No wave was the waste product
of "Taxi Driver,"

00:47.668 --> 00:52.362
Times Square, the Son of Sam,
the blackout of '77--

00:52.397 --> 00:54.226
the desperate need
to violently rebel

00:54.261 --> 00:57.333
against the complacency
of a zombie nation

00:57.367 --> 01:01.164
dumbed down
by sitcoms and disco.

01:01.199 --> 01:03.097
♪

01:03.132 --> 01:05.651
We were howling with delight,

01:05.686 --> 01:07.239
laughing like lunatics

01:07.274 --> 01:10.208
in the madhouse
that was New York City...

01:10.242 --> 01:11.726
♪

01:11.761 --> 01:14.384
Thrilled to be rubbing up
against the freaks

01:14.419 --> 01:17.663
and other outcasts
who somehow...

01:17.698 --> 01:20.252
for some unknowable reason,

01:20.287 --> 01:22.634
had all decided
to run to land's end

01:22.668 --> 01:27.328
and, all at once,
scream their bloody heads off.

01:27.363 --> 01:30.193
[loud distortion]

01:30.228 --> 01:31.746
all: [chanting]
It's our fucking park!

01:31.781 --> 01:33.472
[upbeat rock music]

01:33.507 --> 01:35.405
both: ♪ I took a walk
through this ♪

01:35.440 --> 01:38.408
♪ Beautiful world

01:38.443 --> 01:43.275
♪ Felt the cool rain
on my shoulder ♪

01:43.310 --> 01:47.210
♪ Found something good
in this ♪

01:47.245 --> 01:49.626
♪ Beautiful world

01:49.661 --> 01:54.252
♪ I felt the rain
getting colder ♪

01:54.286 --> 01:55.770
♪

01:55.805 --> 01:58.773
- ♪ La, la
- ♪ Sha la, la, la, la

01:58.808 --> 02:01.155
♪ Sha la, la, la, la

02:01.190 --> 02:04.917
- ♪ Sha la, la, la
- Sha la, la, la, la ♪

02:04.952 --> 02:08.404
♪ Sha la, la, la, la, la

02:11.821 --> 02:14.237
[loud beep]

02:14.272 --> 02:17.551
[sirens wailing]

02:17.585 --> 02:21.279
[horns honking]

02:23.281 --> 02:24.937
- Nothing but
a bunch of crack heads,

02:24.972 --> 02:27.216
Dope fiends and
motherfuckers

02:35.327 --> 02:39.607
- This is a show
about a very special place...

02:39.642 --> 02:42.300
[whirring]

02:42.334 --> 02:44.716
A very special time...

02:44.750 --> 02:47.339
[horn blaring]

02:47.374 --> 02:50.584
And some very special people.

02:50.618 --> 02:54.277
So much happened,
so much began

02:54.312 --> 02:57.625
on New York's Lower East Side.

02:57.660 --> 03:01.319
Those buildings
are still there.

03:01.353 --> 03:02.768
Yeah, all of them.

03:02.803 --> 03:06.358
Yeah, I mean, I know
every corner I ever drank

03:06.393 --> 03:08.360
by order of, like,
preference, you know,

03:08.395 --> 03:09.982
'cause there was some,
you know,

03:10.017 --> 03:11.639
you'd really rather
not to go to.

03:11.674 --> 03:13.986
That was, like, sort of, like,
you know, a last resort.

03:14.021 --> 03:15.367
- Yeah.

03:15.402 --> 03:16.851
- Somewhere, uh...

03:16.886 --> 03:19.613
there was a hole, a big hole
in the wall right there.

03:19.647 --> 03:23.996
Basically like a car-sized
hole in a wall.

03:24.031 --> 03:27.379
You'd step into
an abandoned space.

03:27.414 --> 03:29.519
I didn't know
any spots down there.

03:29.554 --> 03:31.038
I mean, people would take me,
of course.

03:31.072 --> 03:33.385
- Yeah, yeah.
- But it was not my regular.

03:33.420 --> 03:37.631
My regular was here,
at Executive and Laredo

03:37.665 --> 03:40.737
were my preferred.

03:40.772 --> 03:42.808
But for a while,
I had to go specifically--

03:42.843 --> 03:44.707
- Hot zone.
- Yeah.

03:50.057 --> 03:51.921
[film reel clicking]

03:51.955 --> 03:55.269
[jazzy rock music]

03:55.304 --> 04:02.276
♪

04:02.311 --> 04:04.382
The Lower East Side
was in many ways

04:04.416 --> 04:05.935
the cradle of New York.

04:05.969 --> 04:07.419
[clears throat]

04:07.454 --> 04:09.697
The Lower East Side
was in many ways

04:09.732 --> 04:11.285
the cradle of New York,

04:11.320 --> 04:13.494
where new arrivals
first settled,

04:13.529 --> 04:16.048
built communities,
and later, moved on,

04:16.083 --> 04:18.982
only to be replaced by others.

04:19.017 --> 04:26.231
♪

04:30.097 --> 04:31.857
In the New York City
of the '70s,

04:31.892 --> 04:34.584
nearly bankrupt,
riddled with corruption,

04:34.619 --> 04:37.518
the Lower East Side,
particularly Alphabet City,

04:37.553 --> 04:39.382
was left to fend for itself.

04:39.417 --> 04:43.455
♪

04:43.490 --> 04:48.391
Huge swaths of it abandoned,
ruined, or simply empty.

04:48.426 --> 04:51.325
♪

04:51.360 --> 04:54.604
Much of it became an open-air
supermarket for drugs,

04:54.639 --> 04:58.332
whole blocks taken over
by organized drug gangs.

04:58.367 --> 05:02.025
♪

05:02.060 --> 05:04.545
Rents were cheap,
and the neighborhood started

05:04.580 --> 05:06.616
to attract a newer,
highly energized,

05:06.651 --> 05:10.413
and creative group of people
who wanted to make things--

05:10.448 --> 05:15.038
Music, poetry,
movies, and art.

05:15.073 --> 05:21.493
♪

05:21.528 --> 05:25.117
It seemed at the time,
everybody was a star

05:25.152 --> 05:29.432
and, for a while at least,
that it was a golden time.

05:29.467 --> 05:30.882
But it was dangerous.

05:30.916 --> 05:33.367
You lived down here,
you had to be tough

05:33.402 --> 05:36.853
and talented
and often very quick.

05:36.888 --> 05:41.651
♪

05:41.686 --> 05:43.481
Now...

05:43.515 --> 05:46.138
things are different...

05:46.173 --> 05:48.071
very different.

05:48.106 --> 05:49.935
- Everybody together.
Ready?

05:49.970 --> 05:52.455
One, two, three.

05:52.490 --> 05:55.182
Pick those feet up six inches
and hold.

05:55.216 --> 05:57.943
Bring that arm over.
Pin the wrist, let's go.

05:57.978 --> 05:59.738
Is everybody clear?
- Yes.

05:59.773 --> 06:01.809
- I can't hear you.
all: Yes!

06:01.844 --> 06:03.880
- Okay, on three.
One, two, three, let's go.

06:03.915 --> 06:07.056
["I Love My Life"
by Harley Flanagan]

06:07.090 --> 06:12.889
♪

06:12.924 --> 06:15.547
♪ My love,
what's your number? ♪

06:15.582 --> 06:17.756
♪ Don't know if I'll survive

06:17.791 --> 06:20.483
♪ Street crime and violence

06:20.518 --> 06:22.554
♪ All I see is grime

06:22.589 --> 06:24.936
♪ But one thing that I know

06:24.970 --> 06:30.182
♪ That's why I love, love,
love my life ♪

06:30.217 --> 06:32.771
♪

06:32.806 --> 06:35.705
So, I mean, this is pretty much
some of the last remnants

06:35.740 --> 06:37.189
of what the Lower East Side

06:37.224 --> 06:39.502
kind of used to be like,
you know?

06:39.537 --> 06:42.125
Good, old-school,
no elevator.

06:42.160 --> 06:43.575
[laughs]

06:43.610 --> 06:45.439
- You didn't live
in this building?

06:45.474 --> 06:47.510
- No, this wasn't the building
I lived in.

06:47.545 --> 06:50.651
This is a squat, though,
that actually became legal.

06:50.686 --> 06:53.240
I was actually in that building
right there.

06:53.274 --> 06:54.862
When I lived in it,
it was--

06:54.897 --> 06:58.866
you know, we had no windows,
no front doors, you know?

06:58.901 --> 07:00.730
You'd find a door
in the street.

07:00.765 --> 07:03.733
You'd put it up and chain it up
yourself, you know?

07:03.768 --> 07:05.977
No running water, I used to...

07:06.011 --> 07:08.462
bathe in the fire hydrant
in front of the building,

07:08.497 --> 07:10.671
and I used to sleep
with my pit bull

07:10.706 --> 07:13.536
so rats wouldn't get too close
to me at night.

07:13.571 --> 07:14.813
- Right?
- You know?

07:14.848 --> 07:17.160
[sirens wailing]

07:17.195 --> 07:20.163
[soft music]

07:20.198 --> 07:21.889
- You actually grew up here.

07:21.924 --> 07:24.098
What was that like growing up--
growing up here?

07:24.133 --> 07:25.548
Being a little kid here?

07:25.583 --> 07:27.274
- My main problem
growing up down here

07:27.308 --> 07:28.896
was that I lived
on a gang block.

07:28.931 --> 07:30.967
- Right.
- The gang on my block

07:31.002 --> 07:32.728
was called the Hitmen,

07:32.762 --> 07:35.178
and, you know,
they were no joke, right?

07:35.213 --> 07:37.491
And I remember, they would be
hanging out on the stoop

07:37.526 --> 07:39.907
on the church across
the street, smoking dust.

07:39.942 --> 07:41.840
All of them
with their golf clubs

07:41.875 --> 07:46.189
and 007 knives, and everybody'd
be listening to...

07:46.224 --> 07:47.846
of all things, Kraftwerk.
- Right.

07:47.881 --> 07:49.641
- "Trans-Euro Express."
- Right.

07:49.676 --> 07:51.056
- They'd be out there screaming
"we're going to kill

07:51.091 --> 07:53.645
the next [...] that comes out
of that building,

07:53.680 --> 07:57.028
and I'm laying there,

07:57.062 --> 07:59.996
thinking, "Oh, I got to go
to school tomorrow, man."

08:00.031 --> 08:01.860
♪

08:01.895 --> 08:04.656
I was never a violent person.

08:04.691 --> 08:06.209
You know, Christ,
I was raised by hippies,

08:06.244 --> 08:09.143
but I was thrown
into a crazy environment

08:09.178 --> 08:12.664
where I had no choice
but to fight my way through it.

08:12.699 --> 08:15.080
I always had a cue ball
and a sock in my pocket.

08:15.115 --> 08:16.530
I'd split your head open

08:16.565 --> 08:18.014
quicker than you could
say "What the--"

08:18.049 --> 08:20.810
[loud distortion]

08:20.845 --> 08:22.881
And it did turn me into a bit

08:22.916 --> 08:25.539
of a problem as a teenager,
you know?

08:25.574 --> 08:26.920
- I would guess.

08:26.954 --> 08:28.542
Wait a minute, I don't
have to guess, I know.

08:28.577 --> 08:29.681
- [laughs]

08:29.716 --> 08:31.787
[heavily distorted punk music]

08:31.821 --> 08:33.892
- The first time I saw you,

08:33.927 --> 08:36.688
you were, famously, that 12-year-old drummer

08:36.723 --> 08:37.965
in the Stimulators.

08:38.000 --> 08:39.829
Your aunt was in the band.
- Yeah.

08:39.864 --> 08:41.693
That was the only reason
we were allowed to play

08:41.728 --> 08:43.695
at most of the clubs
is because

08:43.730 --> 08:47.112
I had a "relative" who was
basically my legal guardian.

08:47.147 --> 08:49.045
I need to get
a vanilla egg cream.

08:49.080 --> 08:50.564
What are you getting?
- Chocolate egg cream.

08:50.599 --> 08:51.841
- Chocolate egg cream.
- Yeah.

08:51.876 --> 08:55.224
One vanilla, one chocolate.

08:55.258 --> 08:58.330
- I got PTSD, man.
It's like, I just feel like

08:58.365 --> 09:00.229
I'm seeing ghosts
when I'm down here, man.

09:00.263 --> 09:03.059
I miss it, though. I tell you--
as much as I paint it

09:03.094 --> 09:08.064
as this horror story,
which it was, I loved it.

09:08.099 --> 09:12.103
You know, it'll always be
a part of who I am.

09:12.137 --> 09:13.380
My man.
- Cheers.

09:13.414 --> 09:15.347
- All right, Ray,
thanks for the egg cream.

09:15.382 --> 09:17.591
- That is a superb egg cream.

09:17.626 --> 09:19.144
- They don't make them
no better.

09:19.179 --> 09:21.077
[static crackles]

09:21.112 --> 09:24.080
[haunting soft music]

09:24.115 --> 09:30.915
♪

09:31.985 --> 09:34.159
- You're always talking
about what?

09:34.194 --> 09:35.851
- I had a signed "The Last"--

09:35.885 --> 09:39.026
What is it? "The Last Words
of Dutch Schultz."

09:39.061 --> 09:42.098
You came here first
as a writer, as a poet.

09:42.133 --> 09:46.275
New York, in your mind, was
where the writer's life was?

09:46.309 --> 09:48.622
- Yeah, well, it was
just the place

09:48.657 --> 09:49.968
that had the most stimulation.

09:50.003 --> 09:52.108
- Was music even
in the back of your head,

09:52.143 --> 09:53.972
or was poetry and writing?

09:54.007 --> 09:57.389
- My model was Dylan Thomas
when I was a teenager.

09:57.424 --> 10:01.324
You know, so being
a drunken womanizer,

10:01.359 --> 10:02.981
that was my ambition.

10:03.016 --> 10:05.190
[laughter]

10:05.225 --> 10:08.193
[upbeat rock music]

10:08.228 --> 10:15.615
♪

10:29.905 --> 10:32.355
- You woke up
in your own lifetime,

10:32.390 --> 10:36.083
open up a paper,
and realized,

10:36.118 --> 10:39.328
"There's, like, a million kids
in Britain dressing like me

10:39.362 --> 10:40.916
and cutting
their hair like me."

10:40.950 --> 10:44.954
And you have this inadvertent,
tectonic effect

10:44.989 --> 10:47.198
on kids all over the world.

10:47.232 --> 10:51.789
- Well, it wasn't inadvertent,
but it was indirect.

10:51.823 --> 10:53.894
I mean, I wanted
to have that effect.

10:53.929 --> 10:57.242
[slow rock music]

10:57.277 --> 11:03.214
♪

11:03.248 --> 11:05.457
Other bands who responded

11:05.492 --> 11:07.839
to the way I was doing things got famous,

11:07.874 --> 11:11.774
so it ended up having this
huge impact and influence.

11:11.809 --> 11:15.329
When I first saw a picture
of the Sex Pistols,

11:15.364 --> 11:17.262
it was like--
I just had to laugh.

11:17.297 --> 11:19.264
- That's a charitable
interpretation of events.

11:19.299 --> 11:22.267
Malcolm McLaren came to
New York and saw the Voidoids

11:22.302 --> 11:24.856
and went back
and built a boy band,

11:24.891 --> 11:27.410
and said, "You're going
to dress like that guy."

11:27.445 --> 11:29.378
- Yeah, I don't really
look at it that way.

11:29.412 --> 11:30.862
- [speaks indistinctly]
- Yeah.

11:30.897 --> 11:33.106
- All right.
- I mean, ideas are free.

11:33.140 --> 11:35.384
I never resented that.
- Mm-hmm.

11:35.418 --> 11:38.214
- But it was funny and strange.

11:38.249 --> 11:39.837
♪

11:39.871 --> 11:43.116
- Cheap rent brought
a lot of people together.

11:43.150 --> 11:44.980
It wasn't just
living spaces were cheap.

11:45.014 --> 11:47.120
There were venues
where you could put

11:47.154 --> 11:48.880
whatever it was
you did out there.

11:48.915 --> 11:52.884
- Yeah, CBGB's didn't exist
until we created it.

11:52.919 --> 11:54.437
I mean, we went and proposed

11:54.472 --> 11:56.957
that we be
the house band there.

11:56.992 --> 11:59.511
- This next number
is called

11:59.546 --> 12:01.513
"I Belong To
The Blank Generation"

12:01.548 --> 12:03.412
[crowd shouting, applause]

12:03.446 --> 12:04.758
One, two, three!

12:04.793 --> 12:07.761
[bright horn music]

12:07.796 --> 12:12.317
♪

12:12.352 --> 12:15.527
- And then your band,
the Voidoids--

12:15.562 --> 12:17.460
what were your expectations?

12:17.495 --> 12:18.841
- I wanted everything

12:18.876 --> 12:21.395
that anybody
who starts a band wants,

12:21.430 --> 12:24.916
but I didn't even quite realize

12:24.951 --> 12:27.988
how weird and uncommercial I was.

12:28.023 --> 12:29.265
[static crackles]

12:29.300 --> 12:34.063
I thought what I was doing
was really catchy.

12:34.098 --> 12:35.547
[laughs]

12:35.582 --> 12:39.137
- Do we over-romanticize
that period?

12:39.172 --> 12:40.207
Was it special?

12:40.242 --> 12:43.486
- I think the creation
of the mythology of the '70s

12:43.521 --> 12:45.868
kind of began
in the mid-'90s.

12:45.903 --> 12:48.008
I can see why people who weren't there

12:48.043 --> 12:49.872
wish they were there, but it goes

12:49.907 --> 12:51.598
against all my instincts
to think that way

12:51.632 --> 12:53.427
just because the idea is

12:53.462 --> 12:55.429
we didn't like
where things were,

12:55.464 --> 12:57.431
so we decided to change them.

12:57.466 --> 12:59.295
- Why are you here tonight?

12:59.330 --> 13:01.884
- I guess we're just interested
to see what's going on.

13:01.919 --> 13:05.094
We saw a bit in--I think
it was "The New Yorker."

13:05.129 --> 13:08.028
More or less,
to see what was happening.

13:08.063 --> 13:10.203
Simple as that.
- How about you?

13:10.237 --> 13:12.446
- It's a fascinating place,
I must say.

13:12.481 --> 13:15.173
It's probably one of the most
interesting places in New York.

13:15.208 --> 13:16.830
Just simply the...

13:16.865 --> 13:19.315
the neon lights
and the crowd here--

13:19.350 --> 13:20.972
it's all very interesting.

13:21.007 --> 13:23.181
- Would you come here again?
- No.

13:23.216 --> 13:24.320
[laughs]

13:24.355 --> 13:27.323
[raucous percussion]

13:27.358 --> 13:31.949
♪

13:31.983 --> 13:34.468
- Have you ever considered
writing a dish-y memoir?

13:34.503 --> 13:36.850
I mean, my God,
it would be 800 pages long.

13:36.885 --> 13:38.058
- Yeah, you know why?

13:38.093 --> 13:40.129
Because so many people
are still alive.

13:40.164 --> 13:42.614
- I mean, people love you.
- Yeah.

13:42.649 --> 13:43.995
They have to say that.

13:44.030 --> 13:45.859
How can you say something mean

13:45.894 --> 13:48.275
about somebody
who might be mean back at you?

13:48.310 --> 13:50.657
- It's an industry.
Are you kidding me?

13:50.691 --> 13:53.660
[groovy music]

13:53.694 --> 14:01.047
♪

14:09.158 --> 14:10.953
- People will ask,
"What was it like

14:10.988 --> 14:12.886
the first time you saw Iggy?"

14:12.921 --> 14:14.094
And I didn't see him.

14:14.129 --> 14:15.958
I heard the music
from down the hall.

14:15.993 --> 14:17.408
I mean, I thought,

14:17.442 --> 14:19.997
"This is the rock and roll
I always wanted to hear"--

14:20.031 --> 14:22.309
something
that was this fierce.

14:22.344 --> 14:26.106
And yet, you could sense--
there was a tune there.

14:26.141 --> 14:28.281
- When I bought "Funhouse"
in high school...

14:28.315 --> 14:29.247
- Yeah.

14:29.282 --> 14:31.249
- I was immediately
ostracized.

14:31.284 --> 14:33.044
- Yeah.
- This was defining music.

14:33.079 --> 14:35.184
And normal people
didn't like it.

14:35.219 --> 14:38.049
- The Ramones met because
they were poor outcasts

14:38.084 --> 14:41.984
in a high school of 5,000
people who liked "Funhouse."

14:42.019 --> 14:43.434
- Right.
- Okay?

14:43.468 --> 14:44.987
They had it all figured out,

14:45.022 --> 14:48.059
that they would sell
as many records

14:48.094 --> 14:50.993
as the great record sellers
would sell,

14:51.028 --> 14:53.064
and in a few years,
they would have so much money

14:53.099 --> 14:56.136
that they would retire
and never have to work again.

14:56.171 --> 14:57.620
- Right, especially
with each other.

14:57.655 --> 14:59.208
- Yeah.
[both laugh]

14:59.243 --> 15:01.935
Guess what. They had to say on the road for another...

15:01.970 --> 15:03.730
- 25 years.
- Yes.

15:03.764 --> 15:05.283
You know where their greatest

15:05.318 --> 15:08.321
financial success
has come from?

15:08.355 --> 15:10.564
"Hey, ho, let's go"...
- Right.

15:10.599 --> 15:15.224
- Sung in football and soccer
stadiums around the world.

15:15.259 --> 15:19.159
The Ramones' estates
are gathering in more money

15:19.194 --> 15:23.439
from five seconds than they
ever made in their--

15:23.474 --> 15:26.718
Is that the measure
of greatness or eternity?

15:26.753 --> 15:28.720
It's one of them.

15:28.755 --> 15:31.723
[calm music]

15:31.758 --> 15:35.762
♪

15:35.796 --> 15:37.488
- So many people died.

15:37.522 --> 15:40.215
So many people
didn't get recognized.

15:40.249 --> 15:42.458
Richard Hell's still living
in the same apartment

15:42.493 --> 15:43.977
he lived in 40 years ago.

15:44.012 --> 15:45.599
- Who likes to move
in New York?

15:45.634 --> 15:47.187
He got a good deal.

15:47.222 --> 15:50.501
The neighborhood got all better
around him, you know?

15:50.535 --> 15:52.261
Iggy was supposed the one

15:52.296 --> 15:55.195
who didn't make it most of all,

15:55.230 --> 15:57.508
and he's still there--
the most dangerous.

15:57.542 --> 15:59.130
- [chuckles]

15:59.165 --> 16:01.788
- God sends us these signs
that there are miracles,

16:01.822 --> 16:03.410
don't give up hope.

16:03.445 --> 16:05.999
What you believe is beautiful
probably is,

16:06.034 --> 16:09.347
but not everyone
will know it in time.

16:09.382 --> 16:16.423
♪

16:26.813 --> 16:29.781
[dramatic music]

16:29.816 --> 16:37.168
♪

16:45.452 --> 16:47.799
- Okay, my name's
Hugh Mackie.

16:47.834 --> 16:52.252
I moved over here in '81
and started this shop in '86.

16:52.287 --> 16:54.289
[metal clatters]

16:54.323 --> 16:55.807
When we opened this shop here,

16:55.842 --> 16:58.258
we were the only, like,
business on the block.

16:58.293 --> 16:59.673
We were the only,
like, real thing

16:59.708 --> 17:04.057
apart from just mayhem
down here.

17:04.092 --> 17:05.817
[metal clatters]

17:05.852 --> 17:07.819
Basically, it's been
a one-man show

17:07.854 --> 17:09.476
with one person helping me,

17:09.511 --> 17:11.685
and we still fix
old British bikes.

17:11.720 --> 17:14.861
We're really into it,
but nowadays,

17:14.895 --> 17:17.484
there aren't so many people
into it anymore,

17:17.519 --> 17:19.452
and the supply of bikes
is dwindling.

17:19.486 --> 17:22.834
[hammer pounding]

17:22.869 --> 17:24.422
It's gotten to the point now

17:24.457 --> 17:26.562
where I'm the only
bad thing on the block.

17:26.597 --> 17:29.462
I'm now the mess.
I'm now the noise.

17:29.496 --> 17:31.774
I'm the scruffy building.

17:31.809 --> 17:33.569
[indistinct chatter]

17:33.604 --> 17:35.778
It's not that anymore.
It's just not.

17:35.813 --> 17:38.850
I mean, it's super-expensive
restaurants,

17:38.885 --> 17:42.233
which come and go
every five years.

17:42.268 --> 17:44.235
High-heeled girls
with mink coats

17:44.270 --> 17:47.307
are out getting into fancy
schnitzel restaurants,

17:47.342 --> 17:51.449
and they're standing on rats,
and they think that's cool.

17:51.484 --> 17:52.864
What they don't know is that

17:52.899 --> 17:56.178
before the restaurants were
here, there were no rats.

17:56.213 --> 17:58.491
So now all these, like, rich
people are coming down here

17:58.525 --> 18:00.217
and standing on rats
and think

18:00.251 --> 18:03.737
that's East Village,
and it never was, you know?

18:03.772 --> 18:05.222
So...

18:05.256 --> 18:07.879
[engine revs]

18:07.914 --> 18:10.882
[tense music]

18:10.917 --> 18:18.269
♪

18:45.434 --> 18:48.437
- How hard was it to--
if you're coming to New York,

18:48.472 --> 18:50.370
a section of New York
that's completely broke--

18:50.405 --> 18:51.785
You are broke.
You're going to be an artist,

18:51.820 --> 18:56.376
and not just art,
but fairly confrontational.

18:56.411 --> 18:59.379
How committed do you have to be
to do that,

18:59.414 --> 19:01.174
particularly at that time?

19:01.209 --> 19:03.314
- I think that...

19:03.349 --> 19:05.592
contrarily, it hasn't
been that hard.

19:05.627 --> 19:08.802
I feel like
I've been very fortunate

19:08.837 --> 19:11.943
to have got
to stay alive here, so...

19:11.978 --> 19:14.532
And I have everything I need.
Look around us.

19:14.567 --> 19:17.673
[mellow rock music]

19:17.708 --> 19:19.537
♪

19:19.572 --> 19:22.540
It's a wonderful
amusement park

19:22.575 --> 19:27.407
of good and bad ideas
all happening at once.

19:27.442 --> 19:29.271
You know how people
immigrate here

19:29.306 --> 19:32.757
to start a new life
and to dream big?

19:32.792 --> 19:35.691
I felt like I needed
to do that as well,

19:35.726 --> 19:38.004
just like the way
that people did

19:38.038 --> 19:39.626
at the turn of the century.

19:39.661 --> 19:43.630
You move to New York
to immigrate to a new land,

19:43.665 --> 19:46.978
to start...a new life.

19:47.013 --> 19:51.431
And that's really what the
Lower East Side is all about.

19:51.466 --> 19:55.849
♪

19:55.884 --> 19:59.853
You know, it was an extremely
rare and wonderful time.

19:59.888 --> 20:03.754
I think only now do I realize
how fortunate I was

20:03.788 --> 20:06.584
that I got to experience
a neighborhood

20:06.619 --> 20:09.587
that had Jack Smith
on 1st Avenue,

20:09.622 --> 20:11.486
that had the Living Theatre,

20:11.520 --> 20:14.454
that had Jonas Mekas
on 2nd Street.

20:14.489 --> 20:16.870
- Who thrilled you back then?

20:16.905 --> 20:20.011
Who was doing stuff
that you just thought

20:20.046 --> 20:21.461
just, "Holy shit,

20:21.496 --> 20:24.602
this is really incredible
and inspiring"?

20:24.637 --> 20:29.469
- Um, well, gosh.
Um, luckily, my friends

20:29.504 --> 20:32.058
that I was working with
were very inspiring.

20:32.092 --> 20:34.888
I loved Joe Coleman's work.

20:34.923 --> 20:37.615
[slides clicking]

20:37.650 --> 20:40.618
[haunting soft music]

20:40.653 --> 20:45.968
♪

20:46.003 --> 20:48.419
- The Lower East Side
at that time

20:48.454 --> 20:49.972
was a destination for me.

20:50.007 --> 20:52.941
There was something,
you know, that compelled me,

20:52.975 --> 20:56.358
you know, to just be there,
and I would paint it.

20:56.393 --> 20:59.844
Squeeze in.
- Yeah. Wow.

20:59.879 --> 21:02.571
Wow.

21:02.606 --> 21:04.504
Oh, yes, you were telling me
about this guy.

21:04.539 --> 21:07.542
- Yeah, yeah, and here,
if you want to use this...

21:07.576 --> 21:10.061
- It's beautiful.

21:10.096 --> 21:13.064
[dramatic music]

21:13.099 --> 21:19.761
♪

21:20.865 --> 21:23.799
- You know, all the paintings are novels, you know?

21:23.834 --> 21:26.319
You know, so it's a dense story,

21:26.354 --> 21:28.701
and the more that you look, the more that you learn.

21:28.735 --> 21:31.704
And it's in nonlinear time,
you know?

21:31.738 --> 21:33.809
Like, you're exploring, you know, at your own pace,

21:33.844 --> 21:35.673
whatever you want to look at.

21:35.708 --> 21:38.435
And someone else might start in a different place,

21:38.469 --> 21:41.403
and, you know, it might tell a different story.

21:41.438 --> 21:47.547
♪

21:47.582 --> 21:49.100
- The performance art,
at what point--

21:49.135 --> 21:51.689
So you came to paint, or did
you come to paint before?

21:51.724 --> 21:55.417
- No, I came to paints,
but the paintings were...

21:55.452 --> 22:00.111
like, implosions, where I was
studying the world around me

22:00.146 --> 22:02.113
and myself inside,

22:02.148 --> 22:07.049
and the performances
became literal explosions.

22:07.084 --> 22:09.431
[screaming wildly]

22:09.466 --> 22:12.434
[heavy rock music]

22:12.469 --> 22:14.609
♪

22:14.643 --> 22:16.473
I learned violence
from my old man.

22:16.507 --> 22:17.922
So I was angry, you know?

22:17.957 --> 22:20.442
When your house is on fire,
you know,

22:20.477 --> 22:21.754
you don't read poetry,

22:21.788 --> 22:24.446
and you don't, you know,
sing a folk song.

22:24.481 --> 22:26.586
You know, you got to scream.

22:26.621 --> 22:29.589
[screaming wildly]

22:29.624 --> 22:36.009
♪

22:36.044 --> 22:37.597
[indistinct chatter]

22:37.632 --> 22:39.875
- I missed all the great art
of the time.

22:39.910 --> 22:43.189
I came for heroin,
and I came for music.

22:43.223 --> 22:45.812
Other than that,
I didn't live here.

22:45.847 --> 22:48.608
But, man, a lot of people
didn't make it,

22:48.643 --> 22:51.749
and I remember,
I guess around 1980,

22:51.784 --> 22:54.890
it was like...
something is happening,

22:54.925 --> 22:56.616
and no one knows what it is.

22:56.651 --> 22:57.893
- You mean the AIDS?
- AIDS.

22:57.928 --> 22:59.826
- Yeah, yeah,
a lot of that time

22:59.861 --> 23:04.624
exists in my mind like a dream,
like an opium dream.

23:04.659 --> 23:07.627
[slowed distorted speech]

23:07.662 --> 23:10.527
[ominous music]

23:10.561 --> 23:12.529
I have these people
that I love

23:12.563 --> 23:16.843
that would just, like,
drop out and fall out.

23:16.878 --> 23:19.846
I'm a little bit sad
that I wasn't there.

23:19.881 --> 23:23.505
I wasn't present,
you know, for them,

23:23.540 --> 23:27.509
because I was too off
in this other world.

23:27.544 --> 23:30.512
[distorted screaming]

23:30.547 --> 23:32.065
♪

23:32.100 --> 23:34.205
But for me,
it was still something

23:34.240 --> 23:36.863
of great beauty
to see that time.

23:36.898 --> 23:38.934
You have Wall Street tycoons

23:38.969 --> 23:41.592
fighting for huge amounts
of wealth,

23:41.627 --> 23:46.563
and you have, like, bums
fighting over, like, pennies.

23:46.597 --> 23:48.530
And it has, like...

23:48.565 --> 23:52.845
you know,
a primal, like, awe.

24:04.304 --> 24:05.961
- It's for Passover,
matzo brei--

24:05.996 --> 24:06.962
special matzo, special days.

24:06.997 --> 24:09.551
[dishes clattering]

24:09.586 --> 24:11.864
[indistinct chatter,
cash register bell dings]

24:11.898 --> 24:14.280
[clattering continues]

24:14.314 --> 24:16.696
[man speaking native language]

24:16.731 --> 24:18.111
[upbeat music]

24:18.146 --> 24:20.562
[man speaking native language]

24:20.597 --> 24:22.115
- [laughs]

24:22.150 --> 24:23.772
- Yes, sir.
- I've been coming here

24:23.807 --> 24:25.187
since 1966.

24:25.222 --> 24:27.845
- Over 50 years.
- Only 5 years.

24:27.880 --> 24:28.984
- It's family.

24:29.019 --> 24:31.746
[man speaking native language]

24:31.780 --> 24:36.302
[upbeat rock music]

24:36.336 --> 24:38.615
So everyone should come,
but not too many people.

24:38.649 --> 24:39.754
- Yeah.

24:39.788 --> 24:40.996
[man speaking native language]

24:41.031 --> 24:43.999
[dramatic opera music]

24:44.034 --> 24:51.248
♪

25:28.216 --> 25:29.976
- This is one of the places that Keith, Harry, and I

25:30.011 --> 25:31.633
would love to come here.

25:31.668 --> 25:33.186
Jean-Michel would join us,

25:33.221 --> 25:34.981
and we would have good meals here on the regular.

25:35.016 --> 25:36.638
And it was consistently
the exact--

25:36.673 --> 25:38.260
you know it's great
when you can go someplace--

25:38.295 --> 25:40.193
they have the exact same food.
Come on, this is it?

25:40.228 --> 25:42.644
- It's still the same?
- Still exactly the same.

25:42.679 --> 25:44.784
- That's encouraging.
- Which is great, it's great.

25:44.819 --> 25:45.958
I mean, you know, even though

25:45.992 --> 25:48.201
there's a hotel
three doors away...

25:48.236 --> 25:49.962
- Right.
- And high rises going up,

25:49.996 --> 25:51.791
we can still have
a decent meal.

25:51.826 --> 25:54.794
[groovy music]

25:54.829 --> 26:02.008
♪

26:03.423 --> 26:05.805
- You brought hip-hop culture

26:05.840 --> 26:08.290
to a very finite number
of people initially

26:08.325 --> 26:10.948
on the Lower East Side.
- Yeah. Mm-hmm.

26:10.983 --> 26:13.226
- Totally changed the world.

26:13.261 --> 26:15.677
- ♪ Everybody get funky

26:15.712 --> 26:18.024
[funky music]

26:18.059 --> 26:19.819
♪ Everybody get funky

26:19.854 --> 26:21.752
♪

26:21.787 --> 26:24.134
- Teenagers at that time were
doing something interesting,

26:24.168 --> 26:27.137
so I wanted to find some people

26:27.171 --> 26:29.691
that would listen
to these ideas,

26:29.726 --> 26:31.969
and that's what lead me
to the Lower East Side

26:32.004 --> 26:33.419
and to connect with--

26:33.453 --> 26:35.041
- I guess you met
Glenn O'Brien.

26:35.076 --> 26:36.249
- Glenn O'Brien, yeah.

26:36.284 --> 26:37.837
- ♪ Everybody get funky

26:37.872 --> 26:38.976
- Glenn was key to it all,

26:39.011 --> 26:40.391
because I would read
his column

26:40.426 --> 26:42.428
in "Interview" magazine,
and it was just brilliant,

26:42.462 --> 26:44.741
and I met him,
and he embraced me

26:44.775 --> 26:47.985
and invited me to
be a part of "TV Party,"

26:48.020 --> 26:49.711
which was this underground--

26:49.746 --> 26:52.127
- Oh, I remember it well.
I watched it at the time.

26:52.162 --> 26:54.889
- Hi, and welcome
to "TV Party."

26:54.923 --> 26:56.407
Fred, why don't you tell us

26:56.442 --> 26:59.134
a little bit about what
the Holy Land looks like?

26:59.169 --> 27:01.205
- I want you to know...

27:01.240 --> 27:02.413
[groovy music]

27:02.448 --> 27:05.140
That I've been
to the Holy Land,

27:05.175 --> 27:09.006
and the Holy Land is so funky.

27:09.041 --> 27:10.283
- How funky is it?

27:10.318 --> 27:12.182
- It's funky!
It's funky!

27:12.216 --> 27:14.874
And through that connection is where I met

27:14.909 --> 27:17.774
all these people that listened
to all these ideas I had,

27:17.808 --> 27:22.157
and that was David Byrne, Chris Stein and Debbie Harry,

27:22.192 --> 27:25.160
and so many amazing people that were just like,

27:25.195 --> 27:27.369
"Yeah, tell me more."

27:27.404 --> 27:31.719
[distorted speech]

27:33.341 --> 27:36.793
[indistinct chatter]

27:48.218 --> 27:51.186
[energetic electro music]

27:51.221 --> 27:56.467
♪

27:56.502 --> 28:00.195
- What I think
is under-celebrated

28:00.230 --> 28:02.853
about you guys in particular
was your kindness.

28:02.888 --> 28:05.822
You were famously
really, really supportive

28:05.856 --> 28:07.927
of the people
you came up with--

28:07.962 --> 28:09.826
your contemporaries
and people around you

28:09.860 --> 28:11.344
who weren't doing as well.

28:11.379 --> 28:13.208
You know, let each other sleep
on each other's floors.

28:13.243 --> 28:14.485
- Well, there was nothing
at stake.

28:14.520 --> 28:16.142
both:
There was nothing at stake.

28:16.177 --> 28:17.730
- And I mean this
in a good way.

28:17.765 --> 28:19.490
You were writing hits
from the beginning.

28:19.525 --> 28:21.354
I mean, these are
enduring songs

28:21.389 --> 28:23.356
that people are still
listening to and hold up.

28:23.391 --> 28:25.807
I just think a lot of people
had low expectations.

28:25.842 --> 28:28.085
You didn't.
I mean, you had a plan, yes?

28:28.120 --> 28:31.744
- Well, no. If we had a plan,
we would have made more money

28:31.779 --> 28:34.229
and not got
so completely fucked over...

28:34.264 --> 28:36.507
- Yeah.
- By the industry, as it were.

28:36.542 --> 28:38.509
- We had a plan to survive.
- Yeah.

28:38.544 --> 28:40.995
- We had a plan
to keep going, doggedly.

28:41.029 --> 28:43.998
[electronic music]

28:44.032 --> 28:45.965
♪

28:46.000 --> 28:49.244
But I think the thing that was
so attractive about that period

28:49.279 --> 28:51.108
was you weren't locked in

28:51.143 --> 28:53.421
to one format or one form, you know?

28:53.455 --> 28:56.976
It was just--
everybody was doing everything.

28:57.011 --> 28:59.565
♪

28:59.599 --> 29:04.156
- You introduced the entirely
revolutionary notion

29:04.190 --> 29:06.261
that street art...
- Mm-hmm.

29:06.296 --> 29:07.987
- Was in fact, really art.

29:08.022 --> 29:11.577
♪

29:11.611 --> 29:13.544
- The painting that we did on the street

29:13.579 --> 29:16.927
was coming from a place that pop art came from as well--

29:16.962 --> 29:21.069
like popular culture,
magazines, advertising, comics.

29:21.104 --> 29:22.415
And so some of the first people

29:22.450 --> 29:24.452
to buy paintings from me and Jean-Michel

29:24.486 --> 29:26.557
was Chris and Debbie from Blondie.

29:26.592 --> 29:28.559
And then they also commissioned

29:28.594 --> 29:31.148
me, Lee Quiñones,
and Jean-Michel

29:31.183 --> 29:32.563
to do sets and art

29:32.598 --> 29:35.014
and participate
in their music videos--

29:35.049 --> 29:36.084
some of the very first.

29:36.119 --> 29:37.499
♪

29:37.534 --> 29:40.571
- Your support and work
with Fab 5 Freddy--

29:40.606 --> 29:43.229
I mean, look at the soundtrack
to the whole world now.

29:43.264 --> 29:44.472
It's hip-hop.

29:44.506 --> 29:46.508
That connection,
that crossover there,

29:46.543 --> 29:49.580
you guys put considerable
muscle and gravitas.

29:49.615 --> 29:51.824
- I talked to all these
record company guys,

29:51.859 --> 29:55.241
and I'd say 98% of them
told me it was a fad.

29:55.276 --> 29:56.587
- It's not going to last.

29:56.622 --> 29:58.589
- It's going to go away
in five years.

29:58.624 --> 30:02.317
- And you recorded a song
that was hugely...

30:02.352 --> 30:05.251
[light music]

30:05.286 --> 30:08.047
- Well, I will say,
you know, like, we're--

30:08.082 --> 30:09.600
I'm very proud of the fact

30:09.635 --> 30:11.913
that, you know,
we created a format

30:11.948 --> 30:14.916
that didn't exist in rap
until then,

30:14.951 --> 30:18.471
and that is that we wrote
a song that had a rap in it.

30:18.506 --> 30:20.266
- Yeah, those guys
were sampling still.

30:20.301 --> 30:23.200
- The rapping was only
scratching and sampling,

30:23.235 --> 30:26.065
so we, you know,

30:26.100 --> 30:28.343
made it viably commercial.

30:28.378 --> 30:31.519
[groovy music]

30:31.553 --> 30:33.141
- And then, you know,
you had another

30:33.176 --> 30:35.350
earth-shattering event--
"Wild Style."

30:35.385 --> 30:37.628
- I had an idea
that we could make a movie

30:37.663 --> 30:41.115
and show that this rapping,
this dancing,

30:41.149 --> 30:44.118
and this DJ'ing was one thing.

30:44.152 --> 30:46.534
- ♪ Electro

30:46.568 --> 30:48.260
- So I was on a trip
to Germany

30:48.294 --> 30:50.262
not long after
the film had aired,

30:50.296 --> 30:52.229
and I see these kids break-dancing.

30:52.264 --> 30:53.679
I'm like, "What the hell is going on?"

30:53.713 --> 30:55.405
[music skipping]

30:55.439 --> 30:59.374
As I got closer, I noticed
the moves the kids were doing

30:59.409 --> 31:02.101
were the exact same moves
that the Rock Steady Crew

31:02.136 --> 31:03.654
does in "Wild Style."

31:03.689 --> 31:07.382
But I then knew that this was
going to translate globally.

31:07.417 --> 31:09.108
♪

31:09.143 --> 31:10.696
- I remember
that film opening.

31:10.730 --> 31:12.698
That was a nuclear bomb.
- Yep.

31:12.732 --> 31:15.149
- And it ended up being, like,
the second-highest grossing--

31:15.183 --> 31:16.529
- Second to
"Terms of Endearment,"

31:16.564 --> 31:18.531
which not many people
think about now,

31:18.566 --> 31:20.671
but, yeah, we did well.

31:20.706 --> 31:22.570
- You got to love that moment
of corporate terror

31:22.604 --> 31:24.572
in the film industry
when people are looking

31:24.606 --> 31:27.402
at the weekend grosses,
and it's like, "What's this?"

31:27.437 --> 31:29.128
- [laughs]

31:29.163 --> 31:32.131
- "Who is this audience that
